Observation Details: This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

Observation Details: This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

Observation Details: *Rare!! Hiked to the top of the Enchanted Rock dome and noticed swifts straggling the horizon just to the NW of the highest point. Distinctive swift silhouettes with curved, tapering wings and pointy aerodynamic bodies, rapid stiff wingbeats. Appeared solid black against the cloud ceiling, but when an occasional bird dropped closer below the horizon, the white throat, rump patches and wing edges were very striking. Long, harsh chattering calls faintly audible from the flock over the wind. They never came super close to the rock formation, and they moved up and down in altitude a lot, sometimes chasing each other. I scanned the group for any odd outliers during 30 minutes of viewing as they moved around in the high winds, usually coming up with 22-25. 31 counted in one full scan of of the flock as they were high in the air. Although very unusual, they also seemed somewhat suited to the dramatic rock formations of the Llano uplift.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

*Rare!! Hiked to the top of the Enchanted Rock dome and noticed swifts straggling the horizon just to the NW of the highest point. Distinctive swift silhouettes with curved, tapering wings and pointy aerodynamic bodies, rapid stiff wingbeats. Appeared solid black against the cloud ceiling, but when an occasional bird dropped closer below the horizon, the white throat, rump patches and wing edges were very striking. Long, harsh chattering calls faintly audible from the flock over the wind. They never came super close to the rock formation, and they moved up and down in altitude a lot, sometimes chasing each other. I scanned the group for any odd outliers during 30 minutes of viewing as they moved around in the high winds, usually coming up with 22-25. 31 counted in one full scan of of the flock as they were high in the air. Although very unusual, they also seemed somewhat suited to the dramatic rock formations of the Llano uplift.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

Observation Details: There are four traditional communal roosts at Garden of the Gods, used by migrant swifts.  This one is on the west side of the northwest face of South Gateway Rock.  My estimate of 140 individual birds is conservative.  This is just a small part of the larger group exploring the roost before making an entrance.  The entry process to get all the swifts into this communal roost takes at least 15 minutes.  A large group flies overhead before this time, the swifts circling and passing low over the roost location from time to time.

Spent over 90 minutes observing the swift in flight and attempting to capture photos. It flew in sweeping circles over the water for the entire time appearing to hunt insects. It was a sunny but cold day so couldn't imagine there was much to catch. I thought it was a swallow and later attempted to id it as a tree swallow enlisting the help of several much more experienced birders than myself. There were some different colorations and distinctions that made us question that id. After hours of research and study, the consensus id was the White Throated Swift. Photos will be attached.

Continuing bird found by Wolf Jedamski on Sunday January 10th.  Photographed by many with real cameras during this session! Today first seen at 11:53-12:25, 12:28-12:35, 12:44-12:50, 12:55-12:58, 13:00-13:04 and 14:14-14:24, feeding over Curtain Pole Pond. A Merlin flew in from the east at 13:02 and started chasing and diving on the White-throated Swift.  Dives were mostly initiated very close to the swift and missed the swift by only feet or inches 4-5 times, this went on for two minutes over the pond while a good-sized group of birders and birding paparazzi watched on in breathless suspense and dread. The Merlin broke off the unsuccessful chase at 13:04 and flew to the west toward the Tennessee River. The White-throated Swift flew off to the east, and didn’t return to Curtain Pole Pond until 14:14. An amazing drama witnessed by the many birders present. Was able to shoot some handheld iPhone max digitally zoomed video only, will add better screen captures of the frames when able to analyze the footage more completely.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

I noticed shape of wings, body, and tail being that of a swift and not a swallow, after my 30 year old daughter pointed them out to me. Both of us observed the colorations of white underneath the body extending up to the neck. I could see this even better through my Cannon PowerShot SX70 HS camera. Approximate location was N 39.23934 X W 119.72654. We were about to observe them for about 20 minutes when the disappeared. When we returned to the truck and the Peterson Field Guide to Birds of Western North America., we both matched up the same illustration of a white-throated swift to what we has seen. I didn't know my swifts well so did not know what species I was seeing at the time.

Spent over 90 minutes observing the swift in flight and attempting to capture photos. It flew in sweeping circles over the water for the entire time appearing to hunt insects. It was a sunny but cold day so couldn't imagine there was much to catch. I thought it was a swallow and later attempted to id it as a tree swallow enlisting the help of several much more experienced birders than myself. There were some different colorations and distinctions that made us question that id. After hours of research and study, the consensus id was the White Throated Swift. Photos will be attached.

Spent over 90 minutes observing the swift in flight and attempting to capture photos. It flew in sweeping circles over the water for the entire time appearing to hunt insects. It was a sunny but cold day so couldn't imagine there was much to catch. I thought it was a swallow and later attempted to id it as a tree swallow enlisting the help of several much more experienced birders than myself. There were some different colorations and distinctions that made us question that id. After hours of research and study, the consensus id was the White Throated Swift. Photos will be attached.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

There are more than 150 WTSWs = 75 pairs nesting in North Gateway Rock, South Gateway Rock, Tower of Babble, White Rock, Gray Rock, and Sleeping Giant.  A few more pairs nest in lesser rock formations in available cracks. By late June, the numbers increase to over 300 birds with offspring.  Later in the summer flocks of over 50 birds come to four communal roost sites in North Gateway Rock and South Gateway Rock spiraling down in groups of  20-30 over a 30 minute period. This is viewable from four locations in the park where you can get a better estimate of numbers since many of the swifts forage far from their nesting location.
Observation Details: This crack is used as an entrance to a WTSW nest each year.  To fly out, the WTSWs need to use their wings, tails, and feet to climb up about two feet where the can more easily launch into the air.

*Rare!! Hiked to the top of the Enchanted Rock dome and noticed swifts straggling the horizon just to the NW of the highest point. Distinctive swift silhouettes with curved, tapering wings and pointy aerodynamic bodies, rapid stiff wingbeats. Appeared solid black against the cloud ceiling, but when an occasional bird dropped closer below the horizon, the white throat, rump patches and wing edges were very striking. Long, harsh chattering calls faintly audible from the flock over the wind. They never came super close to the rock formation, and they moved up and down in altitude a lot, sometimes chasing each other. I scanned the group for any odd outliers during 30 minutes of viewing as they moved around in the high winds, usually coming up with 22-25. 31 counted in one full scan of of the flock as they were high in the air. Although very unusual, they also seemed somewhat suited to the dramatic rock formations of the Llano uplift.

Observation Details: We discovered a bird repeatedly visiting what became clear was a nest under an overhanging cliff below the road. One adult was wheeling around for a few seconds then visiting the nest, which it did  over and over. Soon it was joined by a second adult, and the pair noisily interacted for a minute or so. They began visiting the nest again - one bird flew in, and two flew out! This happened twice, and now there were four swifts flying around. We realized we had witnessed two young leaving the nest for the first time! The whole family flew around the nest site noisily for another minute before heading off down canyon so the juveniles could explore their exciting new world. What a thrill to witness this incredible event!

I had trouble estimating the number of birds there were so many! Birds came to roost about 15 minutes before sunset - 6:43PM. They impressively gathered high up, slowly swirling downward until circling right in front of the crack where they went to roost. There was no breeze, so you could hear the rush of their collective wings. The exact time transpiring from the first bird going in to the last was one minute fifteen seconds. The photos are frames from a low light video, to be posted when I figure out how to post a video. I did get slo mo and many crashed into each other or into the side of the cliff before being successful.

Continuing bird found by Wolf Jedamski on Sunday January 10th.  Photographed by many with real cameras during this session! Today first seen at 11:53-12:25, 12:28-12:35, 12:44-12:50, 12:55-12:58, 13:00-13:04 and 14:14-14:24, feeding over Curtain Pole Pond. A Merlin flew in from the east at 13:02 and started chasing and diving on the White-throated Swift.  Dives were mostly initiated very close to the swift and missed the swift by only feet or inches 4-5 times, this went on for two minutes over the pond while a good-sized group of birders and birding paparazzi watched on in breathless suspense and dread. The Merlin broke off the unsuccessful chase at 13:04 and flew to the west toward the Tennessee River. The White-throated Swift flew off to the east, and didn’t return to Curtain Pole Pond until 14:14. An amazing drama witnessed by the many birders present. Was able to shoot some handheld iPhone max digitally zoomed video only, will add better screen captures of the frames when able to analyze the footage more completely.

None present until 17:50-1752 when 1-2 were flying over cliff. Then none until 18:09 when 4 appeared over cliff, after sun had left it. Then 18:10 there were suddenly 50+ were flying over cliff. Then from 18:11-18:13 119 swifts were counted entering the roost crack. An additional 6 were flying just after the others entered, then they left view not sure where. Arrival was later tonight than on other recent watches, perhaps to maximize foraging time before entering the roost.

Counted entering roost and estimates of flying birds -- ** Estimated total = 434 flying into roost crack from 17:45-16:11 hr + est 50 still flying at end, -36 that flew out of crack after entering = 448, rounded down to 445.   Summary of observations over whole period: just 4 flying near cliff at 17:07, then occasional sightings of 1-4 flying high through 17:25. arrival of roosting birds with 30 flying at 17:37 ; first seen entering roost crack at 17:45: 40 in crack and 100 flying 17:46; 17:51 100 in 25 out; 17 53 160 in 50 out; 17:55 200 in 50 out; 17:57 260 in 30 out; 17:59 275 in 70 out; 16:01 305 in 60 out (-25 re-exit); 18:07 380 in 20 out;  18:10 last sun on cliff with 410 in (-36 re-exit) and 20 out; 18:12 434 in 50 out. Steady increase in numbers since 17:37 suggests continuing arrival of individuals over period when birds began attending and entering roost for evening.

Locality: 14 Crest Rd W, Rolling Hills US-CA 33.75691, -118.35637
Observation Details: About 6 days ago I noticed that 2 swifts or swallows were soaring at eye level above the Portuguese Bend Canyon (1600" or so above sea level). Had not seen either for several months. Next day it looked like two black swifts and one chimney swift soaring above the canyon and over the house (chimmey much smaller and flaring their tail frequently, wings wider). Next day with binoculars watching for 15 minutes about 10 black swifts? ( sharp pointed wings but couldn't see any fork in tail, closed- looked straight across ,couldn't see even a small fork as soared rapidly around, looked like no color at all even when about 30-40 ft overhead. Saw 2-3 smaller swift like birds dark, flaring tail intermittently. They looked just like a chimney swift pics. Today I looked out and saw a a large flock of swifts soaring at eye level (+ above and below). Got binoculars and about 15+ of them were clearly white-throated with both the white on chest, chin, and back flanks obvious. Again there were about 3 much smaller swift-like birds flaring their tails like a very wide fan just like in National Geographic Birds.., and their wings a bit wider. Much larger flocks of swifts are normally 300+ feet above the house when I see them but at times they will come down to enjoy the canyons wind just like the crows, ravens (in large flocks of 20-100, and white-tailed hawks).

Media notes: Photo by Susan Frantz, submitted as part of 1st "physically" documented sight record for Kansas.
Observation Details: A stunning discovery as I was staring out the 5th floor windows of Fraser Hall - a "sandstone bluff" atop a hill. Birds appeared at eye-level, and proceeded to circle/hunt around the building for hours. It was the "old days," so I called the Kansas Rare Bird Hotline and left a message, and got an urgent to call back to try for photos. My officemate, Susan Frantz, retrieved her film camera from down the street and fired away, including a classic shot with the KU Campanile in the background. A convoy of Kansas City birders arrived at around 530pm and the birds were obligingly still around. I even saw one roosting beneath a window ledge overnight and flying out the next morning. Our record was accepted by the KBRC as the "fourth state record, first record verified with physical evidence. Hypothetical status removed." It was even worth a green dot in Sibley's first edition.

Observation Details: Active colony under overhang of Gibraltar Rock (~34.477088, -119.680278), visible with Google 3 D, but not accessible on foot. Constant stream of birds entering and leaving the overhang - cave? - often 15 - 20 birds in the air simultaneously - total of 50 is a guesstimate, could be more - I consider active breeding colony is most likely. If it were just a night roost it would not show constant 'traffic'. Tried getting a direct look and some photos: not easy!! And dangerous: likely will require climbing gear. Flagged breeding category: "carrying food" based on behavior.

This report came via the Abilene Zoo. Two White-throated Swifts were brought to them from a wind farm near Roscoe, Fisher County. Two birds were recovered from the same wind turbine by the same person on consecutive days, Oct 24 and Oct 25, 2023. Each was delivered individually to the zoo on those dates, Oct 24 and 25. The birds were discovered during maintenance. Both appeared to have been roosting in the turbine and had gotten covered with oil or hydraulic fluid. The zoo washed them and began to nurse them back to health. My guess is that the birds found themselves in the area and lacked a suitable place to roost for the night. The turbines probably looked like their only option. Since the two birds are from the same event, I've submitted the same photos and details under both records in eBird.

Counted entering roost and estimates of flying birds -- ** Estimated total = 434 flying into roost crack from 17:45-16:11 hr + est 50 still flying at end, -36 that flew out of crack after entering = 448, rounded down to 445.   Summary of observations over whole period: just 4 flying near cliff at 17:07, then occasional sightings of 1-4 flying high through 17:25. arrival of roosting birds with 30 flying at 17:37 ; first seen entering roost crack at 17:45: 40 in crack and 100 flying 17:46; 17:51 100 in 25 out; 17 53 160 in 50 out; 17:55 200 in 50 out; 17:57 260 in 30 out; 17:59 275 in 70 out; 16:01 305 in 60 out (-25 re-exit); 18:07 380 in 20 out;  18:10 last sun on cliff with 410 in (-36 re-exit) and 20 out; 18:12 434 in 50 out. Steady increase in numbers since 17:37 suggests continuing arrival of individuals over period when birds began attending and entering roost for evening.

Observation Details: White-throated Swifts flying above and below the top of the cliffs in Box Canyon. Box Canyon is a desert canyon that drains into the Gila River. The canyon walls are about 100 ft. vertical for the first mile up canyon from the river. The swifts were flying in and out of cracks high up on the cliff walls. We estimated there to be about 100. The were darting and calling. We spoke to other birders that thought this was late in the year but all 10 people in our group saw them. We agreed that there were about 75 to 100 individuals.
